WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:05.100
Hello, my name is Noah Swingle, and I am a junior mechanical engineering major at the

00:05.100 --> 00:10.240
University of South Carolina, where I also do NASA-funded research on composite manufacturing.

00:10.240 --> 00:15.480
I got the opportunity to compete in the 2017 and 2018 International Space Settlement Design

00:15.480 --> 00:19.840
competitions, and they remain among my fondest memories from high school and one of the best

00:19.840 --> 00:22.000
decisions that I have ever made in my life.

00:22.000 --> 00:27.520
To me, space settlements are so exciting because they represent a major milestone, not only

00:27.520 --> 00:32.240
in space exploration, but in the technological capability of mankind.

00:32.240 --> 00:36.120
But to achieve this goal, you have to develop a certain level of talent and expertise.

00:36.120 --> 00:40.960
I think that's exactly what design competitions like ISSDC do.

00:40.960 --> 00:45.160
I was exposed first-hand to this industry simulation and got to learn about the time

00:45.160 --> 00:48.880
pressure and deadlines that companies face, about the way that you have to work within

00:48.880 --> 00:51.240
teams to achieve your goals.

00:51.240 --> 00:55.720
These lessons were affirmed to me when I interned at the Boeing Company last summer.

00:55.720 --> 01:01.000
To me, the favorite part of competing in ISSDC wasn't necessarily the challenge of

01:01.000 --> 01:04.720
it or the way that I learned from it, but the people that I interacted with.

01:04.720 --> 01:09.080
I got to work with brilliant young students from around the world, forge friendships with

01:09.080 --> 01:14.080
people from other continents, and learn from industry-leading scientists and engineers.

01:14.080 --> 01:17.800
I can say without a doubt that I would not be where I am without competing in ISSDC,

01:17.800 --> 01:20.600
and I cannot be more thankful for the people who are involved with it.

